            <div id="research" class="section">
                <h2>Research Projects</h2>
                
                <div class="project">
                    <div class="title">The Digital Sallust Archive</div>
                    <div class="description">
                        A comprehensive digital edition of Sallust's works with advanced search capabilities, 
                        linguistic analysis tools, and intertextual connections to contemporary sources. 
                        This project aims to provide scholars with new ways to analyze rhetorical patterns 
                        and historical methodologies in Late Republican historiography.
                    </div>
                    <div class="status">Status: In development (funded by NEH Digital Humanities Start-Up Grant)</div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="project">
                    <div class="title">Civil War Narratives in Ancient Historiography</div>
                    <div class="description">
                        Comparative study examining how different ancient historians (Sallust, Livy, Tacitus, 
                        Appian) constructed narratives of civil conflict. Focus on rhetorical strategies, 
                        moral frameworks, and political implications of their historical accounts.
                    </div>
                    <div class="status">Status: Manuscript in preparation</div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="project">
                    <div class="title">Women in Roman Historical Texts</div>
                    <div class="description">
                        Analysis of the representation of women in Roman historiography, examining how 
                        female characters function within broader narratives of political and social change. 
                        Particular attention to the intersection of gender, class, and political agency.
                    </div>
                    <div class="status">Status: Early research phase</div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
